        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>There are relatively few sub-mm observations of the pc-scale nuclear region of NGC 2110. Based on observations at other wavelengths, however, we estimate the continuum level to be ~100 mJy. Assuming that the SiC2 feature strengths behave similarly to NGC 1068, we therefore anticipate the (peak) emission features to be ~500 mJy, and hence request a desired sensitivity per pointing of 5 mJy to try to ensure unambiguous detection. Even if some of the targeted emission lines are markedly weaker than anticipated, the specified sensitivities should still yield a S/N of 5 down to 25 mJy. The targeted SiO (8-7) shock tracer lines are expected to be stronger than those of SiC2.

Line width estimates are based on those of other SiO and SiC2 bands observed in extragalactic and stellar sources respectively, and are expected to be broad (&gt;= 50 km/s; see Fig. 3), and so broad spectral windows are preferred, even with smoothing factors of 2-4. It is expected that (if necessary) the targeted spectral lines could be averaged to a velocity resolution of (at least) 2 km/s (as used in the OT sensitivity calculation) and still be scientifically useful. If the lines are weak against the continuum we will investigate the possibility of stacking them to provide a usable line strength metric. Even in the event that some of the targeted lines are not seen, the proposed spectral setup will still yield data suitable for SiO and continuum imaging.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Line width estimates are based on those of other SiO and SiC2 bands observed in extragalactic and stellar sources respectively, and are expected to be broad (&gt;= 50 km/s; see Fig. 3). The velocity resolutions specified should therefore be sufficient for the resolution of the line profiles, even with the spectral averaging factors of 2-4 specified here.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>NGC 2110 is at a distance of 32 Mpc (Mason et al. 2010), meaning that an angular size of 1" corresponds to 155 pc. Mason et al. (2010) were able to constrain the position of the 10- and 18-micron dust emitting region to r &lt; 32 pc, but they were unable to conclusively distinguish between  emission from the inner NLR and toroidal clumping effects. For (e.g.) the Band 7 SiC2 lines specified here, we therefore request a desired angular resolution of 0.15" (= 22.5 pc), in order to (at least) impose tighter constraints on the emitting region. The short imaging observation of Mason et al. (2009) with a FWHM ~ 0.42" suggests no evidence of low-level extended emission. To allow for the possibility of more extended low-level emission that is detectable in the sub-mm (which is to be expected, based on the more recent NIR maps by Durre &amp; Mold), however, we request a maximum angular size for these ALMA observations of 2". This will still allow us to map any such extended structure with a single telescope pointing.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
