        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Krips et al. (2011) measured HCN emission features in NGC1068 to be at least 500 mJy. On the basis of observations of HCN and SiC2 in a dense, dusty Galactic environment (Cernicharo et al. 2010), we anticipate that the integrated SiC2 line emission will be approximately half this value (250 mJy), against an SMA-measured continuum of ~50 mJy. Should some of the targeted molecular lines prove to be significantly weaker than this in practice, a s/n of 5 should still be achievable down to 25 mJy. We hence request a desired sensitivity per pointing of 5 mJy to try to ensure unambiguous detection in either emission or absorption. The targeted SiO (8-7) shock tracer lines are expected to be stronger than those of SiC2. 

Line width estimates are based on those of other SiO and SiC2 bands observed in extragalactic and stellar sources respectively, and are expected to be broad (&gt;= 50 km/s; see Fig. 3), and so broad spectral windows are preferred, even with smoothing factors of 2-4. If the lines are weak against the continuum we will investigate the possibility of stacking them to provide a usable line strength metric. Even in the event that the SiC2 lines are not seen, the proposed spectral setup will still yield data suitable for SiO and continuum imaging.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Line width estimates are based on those of other SiO and SiC2 bands observed in extragalactic and stellar sources respectively, and are expected to be broad (&gt;= 50 km/s; see Fig. 3). The velocity resolutions specified should therefore be sufficient for the resolution of the line profiles, even with the spectral averaging factors of 2-4 specified here.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>NGC 1068 is at a distance of 14.4 Mpc (Jaffe et al. 2004), meaning that an angular size of 1" corresponds to ~70 pc. The circumnuclear dust structure has been been estimated by Jaffe et al. to be 3.4 pc across (~0.05"). Although this means that we do not expect to resolve the very centermost region, the proposed observations will still allow us to produce maps of the surrounding area directly comparable to the best NIR dust maps currently available and allow us to clearly identify structure associated with small-scale dynamics (e.g. shocks; see Fig. 5.). We will also still be able to test for the presence of SiO and SiC2 in the central region, and the requested largest angular structure size (2.6") will allow us to map any SiO, SiC2 and continuum emission in the surrounding environment on a scale comparable to the Krips et al. (2011) HCN detections, the CO (2-1) extended torus simulations of Maiolino (2008; Fig. 4) and the Muller Sanchez et al. (2009) IR maps with a single telescope pointing.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
