    <prp:abstract>We plan to use SiO and SiC2 as tracers of Si-rich dust/gas interaction in two Seyfert 2 circumnuclear tori on scales comparable to the best IR maps.

Although most Seyfert 2 galaxies exhibit 10- and 18-micron silicate (SiO) dust absorption due to their nuclei being observed through a circumnuclear torus, this is not always the case. Several Seyfert 2 galaxies exhibit MIR SiO dust emission. It is currently unclear if this is due to the presence of a narrow-line region or gaps in a clumpy torus. Furthermore, Seyfert 2 galaxies with MIR SiO absorption have differing SiO profiles. The chemistry of the dust consequently remains uncertain, having been attributed both to SiO and SiC.

To address these issues, we propose to observe NGC 1068 and NGC 2110 using Band 7 SiO and SiC2 lines. The resulting data will (i) provide direct submm counterparts to the best existing NIR maps of circumnuclear gas/dust morphology, (ii) test the usefulness of SiC2 as a dust tracer, (iii) help to differentiate between competing morphology models, and (iv) differentiate between dust models invoking SiO and SiC dust.</prp:abstract>
